Reflection on BSV Demo: What Makes a Good Demo?
I should have written this a year ago, when DSR first showed the BSV in executive demos and during the 2022 Fall Symposium. Here are some design decisions that might provide valuable insights for fellow designers and prototypers
CHOOSING THE RIGHT FORMAT FOR A DEMO
In the past, I learned a valuable lesson about choosing the right format to demo. During a game jam in school, my team created a platformer and puzzle game with three levels that took a few minutes each to complete.
While everyone who played our game enjoyed it and couldn't put down the controller, we only won third place because not enough people had the chance to play our game. The games that won first and second places were both multiplayer games that took about one minute to play.

When the DR team was planning for the executive demo, they initially wanted to reuse the original Buttersoctch demo or use a user study app developed by the APS team (Because they are too nice and afraid to ask for a new demo app due to very tight timeline).
However, I believed this was a missed opportunity as the demo needed to impress executives in a short amount of time (~5 minutes max) and focus on the technology without diverting the discussion. The original Buttersoctch demo was designed for high resolution only and didn't highlight the benefit of varifocal, while a user study app might feel tedious and sometimes need to fuzzy the experience focus to have an unbiased study.
Therefore, the central idea for the BSV demo was to showcase high-detailed, well-tuned lighting and high-resolution objects that users could pick up and examine at various distances, emphasizing close distance interaction. This format allowed us to effectively communicate the benefits of the technology to executives and symposium attendees.

BREAKING GOOD DESIGN PRACTICES FOR A BETTER DEMO
As a designer/developer, we typically strive to follow good design practices to provide users with a positive experience. However, in the case of the BSV demo, breaking these practices is what makes it effective.
This may seem counterintuitive, but it's because many VR best practices are aimed at working around technological limitations. For current-generation VR headsets, it's important to avoid high spatial frequency details such as small text or detailed textures, which can be difficult to read and introduce screen door and aliasing effects. Placing objects 1.5 meters away helps prevent Vergence-Accommodation Conflict (VAC) since that's where the focal plane is located in current-generation headset. If the BSV demo followed these guidelines, people might not fully appreciate the benefits of the technology. They might think, "I can already play Beat Saber well on Quest 2, so why do I need higher resolution or varifocal?" (Learned this concept from Yusufu Sulai from one of the meeting I don't quite remember why I was there). Therefore, for demos like BSV, it's crucial to identify what doesn't work well in current headsets and showcase how research prototypes excel in those areas, so people immediately see the value of new technologies.

QUICK PROTOTYPE FEEDBACK AND ITERATIONS
Quick prototype feedback and iterations are essential for designers to improve their work. It allows them to receive constructive feedback from stakeholders, which can help identify areas that need improvement. This process also helps stakeholders learn what works and what doesn't in the design, leading to a better final result. However, some designers may be hesitant to share their progress because they feel it is not ready yet. By sharing WIP (Work In Progress), designers can receive feedback early on, which can help them iterate and improve their designs. Ultimately, this process leads to a more polished and effective final product.

In BSV demo, we started from a modified ISDK sample scene, which was good for showing the team what type of interaction I had in mind even if the model included was not ideal for high resolution and varifocal headset.
We went through a lot of iterations to find what 3D objects worked well or not through back-and-forth discussion. At one point, we added an movable eye-chart where the size was independent of distance, which was critical to measure the varifocal aspect; however, we found that it caused confusion to audience who did not work in this area, and eventually decided to take it out.
The entire BSV demo started and finished in around two weeks, so the rate at which I updated the team was like twice a day. While this may have been too frequent for a normal project, updating progress to the team as frequently as possible allowed me (as the designer) to gather enough quality feedback to make adjustments during the process. The app was simple to implement, but all those quick turnarounds, back-and-forth between design and feedback, were what made this demo successful.